	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>You have what is at first glance a very strong basic core group.&nbsp;&nbsp;But keep in mind that every group is dependant on a few things, i.e. location/mobs, levels, gear, etc.  There are several scenarios i can think of (namely some spots in Old Sebillis where i actually prefer a good rogue or monk to a wizzy, in heavy pull/fast spawn environments, more melee = less down time = more exp.  Also, while enchies cant touch shaman when it comes to slowing, they are still very good at it.  If it was a perfect world we could always get a perfect group, but it isnt, thats half the fun IMO.  Also zone makes a big difference..outdoors a druid is absolutely invaluable as a group support member.  they still have the nice nukes and evac, as well as some very desireable group buffs.  wizzy's are essential against hi resist mobs.  with that said...on to my favorite support class that is often overlooked and underappreciated...the high level bard.  These guys are awesome..they stack mana regen in addition to clarity/c2, they heal in down times, they keep Tank sta/speed/str/AC up, they are great pullers, they are great crowd control since their mezz was fixed, they charm, they tank (not so great as tanks but do better than a mob slamming on your nuker or enchie..)  and if they are the self sacrificing type, they can almost ALWAYS pull aggro to themselves in a nasty fight.  In summation..i think group composition depends more on location and individual abilities of the players than a set "perfect" group.  Have fun, and LEARN TO USE ASSIST DAMMIT!  (hehe, sorry, i think that is the single MOST important lesson in the whole game, stop killing those poor enchies!)<br><br>-just the musings of a 55 warrior, i am barbarian and not so bright, so take it for what its worth to you.</p>&nbsp;<br> <